abstract: Hon. WILLIAM DUBOSE died at his plantation and residence, in St. Stephen's Parish, S. C., on Saturday last, in the 68th year of his age. abstract: People know enough, we suspect, not to become excited because they hear that the President is "fiery." They have heard too much of it since Mr. PIERCE was inaugurated, to believe that his bluster generally proves serious. abstract: The two branches of the Legislature are working most vigorously for the accomplishment of the duties required and expected of them. abstract: Capt. H. MOODY reports that he left Liverpool for New-Orleans January 30, with a cargo of salt. Five days out took a heavy gale from W.N.W., accompanied with a heavy sea; was boarded by it several times, and lost binnacle, bulwarks, hatch house, split sails, and partly filled the cabin with water. The ship commenced leaking, and increased till the 25th ult., when she leaked so bad that both pumps would hardly keep her free.

abstract: Mr. JAMES T. BRADY lectured before the Mechanics Institute, last evening, on "The Influence of Useful Inventions on Social Life." abstract: The steamship Isabel has arrived at Charleston, and brings advices from Havana to the 25th inst. Much excitement prevailed at Havana on the morning of the 22d inst., in regard to the execution of Don RAMON PINTO. To such a pitch had the feeling on the subject reached, that the Captain General had not been seen in public since the event.
